defaultOur understanding is that many companies have plans in place to offer free
default of charge ASHP installations along the lines of the “rent-a-roof” model that was prevalent when solar PV subsidies were launched. In the case of solar PV the householder was offered free solar panels on the basis that they would get the benefit of any “fr
defaultee” electricity produced whilst the investing company was able to claim the Feed in Tariffs (
defaultFiTs
default) for each kW of metered generation. As such it was possible to see this as a guaranteed “win-win” for each party.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, in the case of ASHPs the picture is not so clear cut – for the householder at least. 
defaultThis is because ASHPs could be offered on a free of charge basis to households who might otherwise be able to afford the normal capital costs associated with the 
defaultinstallation of an ASHP system. This will be particularly true of households containing vulnerable people who might already be in fuel poverty. They will get a free system and the investing company will get a 
defaultguaranteed
default rate of investment return for the 7 
defaultyears that they are able to claim the RHI on the basis of the free/subsidised installation. It is important to note that the return is 
defaultguaranteed
default as RHI payments are made on a deemed rather than a metered basis.
default As such the bulk of the risk sits fairly and
default squarely with the consumer as they will have the gamble as 
defaultto whether the ASHP system will deliver what it says on the tin. Much of the evidence to date, which is detailed in the enclosed analysis, shows that the odds are not great:
