default&#xa0;
defaultThe key to whether heat pumps deliver value for money or not is the
defaultir
default Coefficient of Per
defaultformance (
defaultCoP
default)
default. Heat pumps extract heat from the ground or air and redirect the heat for space heating and hot water. 
defaultCoPs
default represent the ratio of heat produced per unit of electricity consumed in generating that heat. A 
defaultCoP
default of 3 means that 3kWh of heat are output for 1k
defaultWh of electricity used to run the pump. Higher 
defaultCoP
default values represent relatively more efficient heat delivery. 
defaultUnder an EU Directive, h
defaulteat pumps must achieve a 
defaultCoP
default of 2.9 before their energy can contribute to the renewable energy target. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA study of install
defaulted heat pump performance published by the Energy Saving Trust on the 8
defaultth
default September 2010 – “
defaultGetting Warmer: a field trial of heat pumps”
default revealed that the actual performance of heat pumps installed in the UK was surprisingly poor. The study was financed by 
defaultthe heat pump industry and based on a sample of sites where pumps had been installed pre-selected by the industry. The pumps were installed and accredited through the 
defaultMicrogeneration
default Certification Scheme’s immediate predecessor, the Clear Skies programme. 
defaultThe study showed that only 1 of the 22 properties
default with GSHPs
default achieved th
defaulte 2.9 threshold
default, and only 9 of the 47 sites with ASHPs achieved the standard. REF commented on this report: “
defaultThe risk of premature adoption and consumer disenchantment is clearly real,
default thus raising the spectre of a 
defaultUK
default heat pump tragedy… On the basis of this study, there seems a distinct risk that some heat pumps will be subsidised even though they fail to meet the minimum standard for being considered a renewable energy source. If, on t
defaulthe other hand, government withdraws subsidies from such installations, well-meaning householders may discover after investing heavily in a heat pump that their installations fail to come up to the required EU standard, and thus forfeit entitlement to RHI p
defaultayments” (“Renewable Heat Initiative”, September 2010).
default&#xa0;
defaultA 
defaultJoseph 
defaultRowntree
default Foundation study in Elm Tree Mews in 
defaultYork
default 
defaultechoed these results:
default a communal 
defaultGSHP
default was installed with a nominal design 
defaultCoP
default efficiency of 3.2-3.5. Despite a number of interventions, thr
defaultoughout the year of monitoring the delivered 
defaultCoP
default efficiency was 2.15 – that is, it failed the renewab
defaultle
default, and would not be 
defaultgood value for the householder, nor contribute towards national renewable targets. 
defaultE
defaultxpensive technology 
defaulthad been
default installed under a false premise.
default&#xa0;
defaultA report by the Association for the Conservation of Energy, “Improving the energy efficiency of off-grid properties – the role of different heating technologies”, (March, 2011) made assumptions about the 
defaultCoPs
default of heat pump
defaults based on international data: “For GSHPs we assume a lower end 
defaultCoP
default of 2.3 and a higher end 
defaultCoP
default of
default 3.5. For ASHPs we assume  
defaultCoPs
default of 2.15 and 2.7 respectively”. On this basis all ASHPs would fail the test of being renewable since the qualifying ba
defaultr
default, and wo
defaultuld not deliver savings towards the EU targets; 
defaulta smaller number of 
defaultGSHPs would also fail.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Building Services Research and Information Association (BSRIA) is the leading independent 
defaultUK
default laboratory for testing, certification and performance verification 
defaultof a wide range of building services products. Its website discusses the pros and cons of heat pumps: “Test conditions (and hence manufacturers' quoted 
defaultCoP
default data) can therefore differ significantly from actual design and operating conditions”. This confirms
default the essential point that it is not enough to accept pre-installation manufacturers’ quoted 
defaultCoP
default data. BSRIA avert to manufacturers claiming impressive 
defaultCoPs
default but say BSRIA, “This data should be treated with caution”. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Energy Savings Trust has now publis
defaulthed Phase 2 of its testing on pumps (“The Heat is On”, May 2013). The bulk of this work involved a series of interventions on 32 of the failing Phase 1 sites over a three year period. In 12 cases the “interventions were “major”. In 10 cases, the interventi
defaultons involved the complete replacement of the pump systems. Even with all this no doubt expensive intervention: “Some sites did not improve, even with major and medium interventions”. The deficiency in performance was especially marked for ASHPs with 6 out 
defaultof 15 still failing to make the renewable grade. From this we deduce that there is no case for continued taxpayer subsidy to ASHPs since even after extensive and costly intervention by experts an unacceptable proportion could not be made to work properly. 
defaultThey would be ruled out as renewable by the EU and energy they generate would not count towards the 
defaultUK
default’s renewable targets. The average performance of ASHPs was under the bar of being counted as renewable.
default&#xa0;
defaultTo be fair, after all this desperate effort over 
defaultthree years, most GSHPs did work properly. How much all this extensive and expensive remediation would cost, and who would bear that cost – the installer or the householder – is a question for bitter experience in the market, but we draw a strong conclusio
defaultn from this that type-rating technology to a standard is a long way from actual installed performance. Let the buyer beware – and let the taxpayer beware of pouring subsidy into a technology that does not make the grade. Government should pay out subsidy o
defaultnly on those pumps tested as having delivered to minimum performance standards after installation. Time after time heat pumps simply do not do what is says on the tin.
defaultDuring cold weather heat pumps perform unacceptablydefault&#xa0;
