defaultWide deployment of heat pumps would put a very expensive strain on the grid networkdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe Revised NPS (Oct. 201
default0) revealed the full implications of a pure electricity play including the electrification of heat: “Generation capacity will need 
defaultat least to doubledefault to meet this demand and, if a significant proportion of our electricity is supplied from intermittent sour
defaultces, such as wind, solar, or tidal, then the total installed capacity might need to 
defaulttriple”default (para.1.66). This is a major driving factor behind the rising cost of energy to householders.
default&#xa0;
defaultDECC fingers heat pumps as a culprit
default: “In the case of heat pumps the 
defaultchallenge to be managed is in the form of significant new electricity demand. Relative to a conventional household, installation of a heat pump could mean a doubling of annual electricity demand. Given heat demand coincides with peak electricity 
defaultdemand, th
defaultis is likely to put additional load on the network when it is most strained. Clearly, roll out of heat pumps at scale will have significant impacts on our electricity network, (
defaultMicrogeneration
default Strategy Consultation Briefing, 23
defaultrd
default December 2010)
default”.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is 
defaulta major driving factor behind the rising cost of energy to householders. The cost of this extra generating capacity is conservatively put at £200bn – Peter Atherton of 
defaultLiberum
default Capital has assessed the infrastructure costs as being £376bn by 2030.
default&#xa0;
default“Network
default costs of a high heat pump deployment scenario are estimated to be £290 per heat pump on a GB-wide basis in 2030 (£390 in 2050). This compares to £1,130 per heat pump in rural areas in 2030 (£1,490 by 2050) (“Assessing the Impact of Large-Scale Deployment 
defaultof Heat Pumps on Electricity Distribution Network Costs”, by Ernst and Young, 2013). These large extra costs will fall on the already hard-pressed consumer.
